<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" data-section=3D"" id=3D"how-to-work-with-dep=
th-of-field-a-step-by-step-approach">How to work with depth of field: a ste=
p-by-step approach</h2>



<p>While knowing the theory is great, it=E2=80=99s important to also unders=
tand how to apply depth of field when out shooting. Here=E2=80=99s my quick=
 step-by-step approach to achieving the precise DoF effect you=E2=80=99re a=
fter:</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading" data-section=3D"" id=3D"step-set-your-camera=
-to-aperture-priority-or-manual-mode">Step 1: Set your camera to Aperture P=
riority or Manual mode</h3>



<p>Most cameras only offer two modes where you can easily control the apert=
ure and therefore the depth of field: <a href=3D"https://digital-photograph=
y-school.com/aperture-versus-shutter-priority-which-shooting-mode/" target=
=3D"_blank" aria-label=3D"Aperture Priority mode (opens in a new tab)" rel=
=3D"noreferrer noopener" class=3D"ek-link">Aperture Priority mode</a> and <=
a aria-label=3D"Manual mode (opens in a new tab)" href=3D"https://digital-p=
hotography-school.com/shoot-manual-mode-cheat-sheet-beginners/" target=3D"_=
blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener" class=3D"ek-link">Manual mode</a>.</p>



<p>So the first order of business is to switch your camera Mode dial over t=
o one of these options. </p>



<p>If you=E2=80=99re a beginner, Aperture Priority mode is probably the bet=
ter pick =E2=80=93 it=E2=80=99ll let you input the aperture, while your cam=
era determines the best <a href=3D"https://digital-photography-school.com/s=
hutter-speed/" target=3D"_blank" aria-label=3D"shutter speed (opens in a ne=
w tab)" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener" class=3D"ek-link">shutter speed</a> for=
 a good exposure. If you=E2=80=99re more advanced, Manual mode will let you=
 select the aperture and shutter speed independently for greater creative c=
ontrol.</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading" data-section=3D"" id=3D"step-determine-wheth=
er-you-want-a-deep-or-narrow-depth-of-field">Step 2: Determine whether you =
want a deep or narrow depth of field</h3>



<p>Carefully observe your scene. Ask yourself: Do I want to blur out the ba=
ckground? Or do I want to keep the entire shot sharp?</p>



<p>Generally speaking, if your background is distracting, it=E2=80=99s best=
 to use a shallow depth of field. But if the background adds to the scene =
=E2=80=93 for instance, it contains beautiful clouds and a stunning mountai=
n range, or it contributes valuable context =E2=80=93 then use a deep depth=
 of field.</p>


