om/digital-photography-school.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/06/depth-of-field=
-photography-104.jpg?resize=3D1500%2C925&amp;ssl=3D1" alt=3D"Depth of field=
 in photography" class=3D"wp-image-253171"></span></figure></div>


<p>If your goal is to achieve a deep depth of field effect, use a wide-angl=
e lens (if possible) and get as far back from your subject as you can witho=
ut sacrificing the composition. Then dial in a narrow aperture =E2=80=93 of=
ten f/8 or beyond is ideal, though see the next section on hyperfocal dista=
nce if you=E2=80=99re not sure what=E2=80=99s best =E2=80=93 focus about a =
third of the way into the scene, and take your shot.</p>



<p>(Quick tip: When you look through your camera=E2=80=99s viewfinder, you=
=E2=80=99re generally seeing a preview of the image at your lens=E2=80=99s =
<em>widest </em>aperture. But many cameras offer a <a aria-label=3D"depth o=
f field preview button (opens in a new tab)" href=3D"https://digital-photog=
raphy-school.com/depth-of-field-preview/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferr=
er noopener" class=3D"ek-link">depth of field preview button</a>; press thi=
s, and you can preview the actual depth of field in real-time before hittin=
g the shutter button. Check your manual to see if it=E2=80=99s an option on=
 your camera!)</p>



<h3 class=3D"wp-block-heading" data-section=3D"" id=3D"step-check-to-make-s=
ure-you-got-the-depth-of-field-right">Step 4: Check to make sure you got th=
e depth of field right</h3>



<p>After you=E2=80=99ve taken an image, especially when you=E2=80=99re just=
 starting out, I highly recommend you check your camera=E2=80=99s LCD to en=
sure you=E2=80=99ve nailed the depth of field.</p>



<p>Take a quick look at the image in playback mode. If your goal is to keep=
 the entire shot sharp, magnify the photo to check the nearest foreground o=
bject and the most distant background object, just to be sure everything lo=
oks good.</p>



<p>If you notice an error, you can always reshoot before the light changes.=
</p>



<h2 class=3D"wp-block-heading" data-section=3D"" id=3D"hyperfocal-distance-=
how-to-get-everything-in-focus">Hyperfocal distance: how to get everything =
in focus</h2>



<p>The <a aria-label=3D"hyperfocal distance (opens in a new tab)" href=3D"h=
ttps://digital-photography-school.com/how-to-find-and-use-hyperfocal-distan=
ce-for-sharp-backgrounds/" target=3D"_blank" rel=3D"noreferrer noopener" cl=
ass=3D"ek-link">hyperfocal distance</a> is a special point of focus in your=
 scene. It=E2=80=99s the distance for a given aperture and focal length tha=
t allows you to maximize the depth of field.</p>



<p>Specifically, when you focus at the hyperfocal distance, your depth of f=
ield&nbsp;will extend from <em>half </em>your point of focus all the way to=
 infinity.</p>



<p>As you can imagine, this is useful when you want to keep the entire scen=
e sharp; you just dial in your preferred aperture, then set your point of f=
ocus at the hyperfocal distance.</p>


<div class=3D"wp-block-image is-style-with-caption">
<figure class=3D"aligncenter size-large" style=3D"width: 460px;"><span clas=
